{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d3da224b-ae22-44dc-b6f2-b2ec74381214","content":"## What happened\n\nApple's native crypto libraries (`Security.framework` / `CryptoKit`) **do not implement DSA**. In earlier .NET versions a compatibility shim kept `DSA.Create()` working on macOS, but .NET 11 removed that fallback. Now `DSA.Create()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS.\n\nLinux and Windows are unaffected because they use OpenSSL and Windows CNG respectively, both of which still support DSA.\n\n## How to fix\n\n**Short-term — use OpenSSL explicitly on macOS:**\n\nInstall OpenSSL (`brew install openssl`) and use `DSAOpenSsl` instead of the platform-default factory:\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Security.Cryptography;\n\nDSA CreateDsa()\n{\n    if (OperatingSystem.IsWindows())\n        return DSA.Create();          // CNG — still supports DSA\n\n    // Linux already uses OpenSSL; macOS needs it installed (e.g. via Homebrew)\n    return new DSAOpenSsl();\n}\n```\n\nThen load the legacy public key and verify as before:\n\n```csharp\nusing DSA dsa = CreateDsa();\ndsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(legacyPublicKey, out _);\nbool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);\n```\n\n**Long-term — migrate to a modern algorithm.** DSA is considered legacy; if you control the signing side, move to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** (supported natively on all three platforms). Keep the DSA path only for verifying old signatures during a transition period.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"39553a16-6f3e-4567-8d77-22002f6a3386","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS when upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason about this from my knowledge.\n\nIn .NET, the `DSA` class on macOS has historically been backed by Apple's Security framework (CommonCrypto/Security.framework). However, Microsoft has been deprecating and removing older cryptographic algorithms across .NET versions.\n\nSpecifically, DSA support on macOS has been a known issue:\n\n- .NET 5+ started warning about DSA on macOS\n- Apple's Security framework never had great DSA support\n\n\n- Starting in .NET 7, `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because Apple's CryptoKit/Security framework dropped DSA support entirely, and .NET relied on the OS-provided implementation on macOS rather than maintaining its own.\n\nThe user is asking about .NET 10 → .NET 11, and since we're in April 2026, .NET 10 would be the current release with .NET 11 in preview. Given the pattern .NET has followed—first deprecating legacy crypto algorithms, then removing them—and knowing that Apple removed DSA support from their modern crypto frameworks, it's likely that .NET 10 still has some DSA functionality but .NET 11 is removing it entirely on macOS, or the exception behavior is changing in some way.\n\nThe practical solutions would be to either use `DSAOpenSsl` if available (though that requires OpenSSL installed separately), bundle OpenSSL through a NuGet package, or migrate away from DSA entirely—though if they're doing legacy signature verification, that last option isn't feasible. The core issue is that macOS no longer provides native DSA support, so .NET has to either rely on an external OpenSSL installation or drop the functionality. NET and works on platforms where OpenSSL is available. On macOS, I'd need to install OpenSSL via Homebrew, while Linux typically has it built in, and Windows uses CNG. I'm considering a platform-specific approach where I check the OS and instantiate either `DSAOpenSsl` for non-Windows platforms or the default `DSA.Create()` for Windows, though I need to verify whether `DSAOpenSsl` is actually available in the version I'm working with.\n\nActually, the real issue is that Apple's native crypto libraries don't support DSA, and .NET 11 removed the compatibility layer that previously made `DSA.Create()` work on macOS—now it just throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. The solution is to install OpenSSL on macOS and use `DSAOpenSsl` instead.","outputTokens":1834},"id":"04b4f224-794a-4c0d-a856-876564200293","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:59:55.741Z","parentId":"abfa155f-06ea-455f-9f8c-7fc8527d9327"}
